   <abstract>Cosa (modern Ansedonia, Italy), a Latin colony founded in 273 BCE on a waterless, calcareous, brecciated limestone hill in Etruria, depended solely on rainwater for its survival and as such the site is provisioned with dozens of features to collect and store water. Previous scholarship notes the necessity of these rainwater harvesting features, however, no complete synthesis of them has ever been undertaken. Furthermore, although ubiquitous in the compluvium/impluvium of the Roman house, rainwater harvesting, and particularly that of non-domestic contexts, has not received emphasis in Classics or archaeology. This study therefore seeks to fill this gap by examining the mechanisms of rainwater harvesting and storage implemented to contend with the environment of Cosa during the Roman Republican and Imperial periods, alongside comparative rainwater harvesting features from the contemporary Mediterranean, in order to understand the settlement's water management scheme and how competitive euergetism associated with monumental rainwater harvesting shaped the colony's history. First, I delve into Cosa's ecology, which made the promontory waterless but the hinterland marshy, and how it dictated the Cosan settlers' acute concern for non-domestic rainwater harvesting. Then, I investigate the socio-political implications of water management, proposing that the non-domestic rainwater harvesting system of Cosa offered an arena for intense competition among local grandees who sought to gain notoriety and power through building and administrating waterworks. I demonstrate how elements of the ecological situation of Cosa effected the settlement, which suffered cyclical periods of growth and decline over its long history. These questions about the colony's approach to water management reveal historical and socio-cultural facets of the colony, such as the euergetic behavior and prestige associated with cistern construction as well as how water-related illness impacted the population.</abstract>
